How Value Objects turn vague primitives into explicit, validated domain concepts

13 min read
Just now

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

PHP makes it incredibly easy to default to primitive types like string, int, and float for almost everything. An email address is a string. A price is a float. A percentage is also a float. The language does nothing to prevent this — any value that matches the primitive type is accepted, whether it makes sense for the domain or not. A string parameter accepts a valid email address just as happily as it accepts "banana".
public function createDiscount(
string $code,
float $amount,
string $currency,
string $type
): void
{
// ...
}This code compiles, but it communicates very little. What exactly does $amount represent? Is it a fixed monetary value or a percentage? Is $currency a valid ISO currency code, or just an arbitrary string? Can $code be empty?
The answers are usually hidden elsewhere: inside scattered validation checks, comments, documentation, or sometimes nowhere at all.
This is known as primitive obsession: the overuse of primitive types to represent concepts that actually have their own rules, constraints, and meaning.
This is not merely a matter of code style. It creates real problems:
▶︎ Validation becomes duplicated
The same rules get repeated across the codebase. An email validation check might appear in a controller, a service class, and a form request. Over time, one of those checks gets forgotten, creating inconsistent behavior.
▶︎ Intent becomes unclear
A float $amount tells you the value is numeric, but not what it means. Is it:

• $10.99?

• 1099 cents?

• 15.0 percent?
The type provides no context.
▶︎ Invalid states become possible
The code allows invalid objects to exist:
new Order('', -50.0, 'usd');Nothing in the type system prevents an empty identifier, a negative amount, or an invalid currency from making its way into the application.
▶︎ Type safety remains shallow
PHP can protect you from passing an int where a string is expected, but it cannot protect you from passing the wrong kind of string. A currency code and an email address are both strings, even though they represent completely different concepts.
The solution is not to eliminate primitive types completely. They are still useful for simple values. The goal is to stop using primitives for concepts that have their own identity, validation rules, and behavior.
When a concept matters in your domain, it deserves a type of its own.

What Value Objects Actually Are
A Value Object is a small, immutable class that wraps a primitive value (or a closely related set of primitives) and gives it meaning within the domain. Instead of representing everything as generic string, int, or float values, a value object creates an explicit type for concepts such as Email, Money, Percentage, or DateRange.
The key characteristic of a value object is that it has no identity of its own. Its meaning comes entirely from the value it contains.
For example, two Money objects representing 1000 cents in USD are considered equal, even if they are separate object instances in memory. The objects themselves do not matter — only the values they represent do.
This is different from an Entity, which is defined by its identity. Two User objects with the same name are still two different users because each one represents a distinct individual with its own lifecycle and identity.
A well-designed value object is also always valid after construction. An Email object cannot exist with the value "not-an-email" because validation happens when the object is created. If the value is invalid, construction fails, and the invalid object never enters your system.
That guarantee is the real power of value objects: once a piece of code receives an Email, Money, or Percentage object, it can trust that the value already satisfies its rules. There is no need for repeated validation checks scattered throughout controllers, services, or business logic. The object itself protects the integrity of the domain.

Characteristics of Good Value Objects
A well-designed Value Object is more than a wrapper around a primitive type. It is a small domain model that protects its own rules and expresses what a value means. The strongest value objects share four important characteristics: immutability, invariants, value-based equality, and encapsulated behavior.
✅ Immutability
A value object does not change after it has been created. Once constructed, its state is fixed forever.
Operations that appear to modify a value object should instead return a new instance containing the updated value.
final readonly class Money
{
private function __construct(
private int $amountInCents,
private string $currency
) {} public function add(Money $other): self
{
return new self(
$this->amountInCents + $other->amountInCents,
$this->currency
);
}
}
Here, add() does not modify the existing Money object. It creates and returns a new one.
Immutability makes value objects safer to use because they can be passed anywhere — between methods, stored in collections, or shared across processes — without worrying that another part of the application will unexpectedly change their state.
✅ Invariants
An invariant is a rule that must always be true for an object to remain valid.
For a value object, these rules belong in the constructor. The object should never be allowed to exist in an invalid state.
final readonly class Money
{
// ... public function __construct(int $amountInCents, string $currency)
{
if ($amountInCents < 0) {
throw new InvalidArgumentException('Amount cannot be negative');
}
if (!\preg_match('/^[A-Z]{3}$/', $currency)) {
throw new InvalidArgumentException(
\sprintf("Invalid currency code: %s", $currency)
);
}
$this->amountInCents = $amountInCents;
$this->currency = $currency;
}
}
The constructor becomes the single entry point where validity is guaranteed.
If object creation succeeds, the rest of the application can trust that the object is valid. There is no need to repeat the same validation logic in every controller, service, or command that uses it.
✅ Equality by Value
Value objects are compared by what they contain, not by where they exist in memory.
Two Money objects with the same amount and currency represent the same value, even if they are different object instances.
final readonly class Money
{
// ... public function equals(Money $other): bool
{
return $this->amountInCents === $other->amountInCents
&& $this->currency === $other->currency;
}
}
While PHP provides object comparison operators, relying on == can make equality rules unclear and dependent on implementation details.
An explicit equals() method makes the intention obvious: these objects are equal because they represent the same domain value.
✅ Encapsulated Behavior
A value object should not only hold data — it should contain the behavior that naturally belongs to that concept.
Instead of spreading money-related calculations across services, controllers, and helpers, keep them inside the Money object itself.
final readonly class Money
{
// ... public function applyDiscount(Percentage $percentage): self
{
$discounted = (int) round(
$this->amountInCents * (1 - $percentage->value() / 100)
);
return new self($discounted, $this->currency);
}
}
Now the rule for how money is discounted exists in one place: the object that represents money.
This keeps domain logic close to the data it operates on, reduces duplication, and makes the code easier to understand. A Money object knows how money behaves, a Percentage object knows what a percentage means, and the rest of the application simply uses these concepts without needing to understand their internal rules.

Before and After: Refactoring Primitive Obsession
The difference between primitive-heavy code and value-object-based code becomes clearer through a simple refactoring example.
Before: Primitive Types Everywhere
class Order
{
private string $customerEmail;
private float $price;
private string $currency; public function __construct(
string $customerEmail,
float $price,
string $currency
) {
$this->customerEmail = $customerEmail;
$this->price = $price;
$this->currency = $currency;
}
public function applyDiscount(float $percentage): void
{
if ($percentage < 0 || $percentage > 100) {
throw new InvalidArgumentException('Invalid percentage');
}
$this->price -= $this->price * ($percentage / 100);
}
}
At first glance, this class looks simple. But the types only describe the shape of the data, not its meaning.
A string can contain a valid email address or "garbage". A float can represent a valid price or -99.0. Another string might contain "USD" or "dollars".
Nothing prevents this:
new Order('garbage', -99.0, 'dollars');The Order class can only rely on whatever validation happened before it was called. If the caller forgets to validate, the invalid state enters the system.
As the application grows, these checks tend to spread across controllers, services, forms, and database layers — creating duplicated and inconsistent validation logic.
After: Domain Concepts Become Types
With value objects, the Order no longer receives vague primitives. It receives objects that already represent valid domain concepts.
final class Order
{
public function __construct(
private readonly Email $customerEmail,
private Money $price
) {} public function applyDiscount(Percentage $percentage): void
{
$this->price = $this->price->applyDiscount($percentage);
}
public function price(): Money
{
return $this->price;
}
}
Creating an order now becomes explicit:
$order = new Order(
new Email('customer@example.com'),
Money::fromFloat(19.99, 'USD')
);$order->applyDiscount(new Percentage(15));
The Order class no longer needs to know how to validate emails, prices, currencies, or percentages. Those rules belong to the objects that represent those concepts.
An Email object guarantees that it contains a valid email address. A Money object guarantees that the amount and currency are valid. A Percentage object guarantees that the percentage is within an acceptable range.
The result is a system where invalid states are rejected as early as possible — at the moment an invalid value is created, not later when it causes unexpected behavior somewhere else.
Value Objects move validation from scattered checks into the domain itself, making the code easier to trust, maintain, and evolve.

Advanced PHP 8.1+ Patterns for Value Objects
Modern PHP provides several language features that make building robust Value Objects easier. Features like readonly properties, enums, and named constructors help enforce invariants, reduce boilerplate, and make domain concepts explicit.
▶︎ Readonly Properties
PHP 8.1 introduced readonly properties, allowing immutability to be enforced by the language instead of relying only on developer discipline.
Once a readonly property has been initialized, any attempt to change it later results in an Error.
final class Email
{
public readonly string $value; public function __construct(string $value)
{
if (!\filter_var($value, FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL)) {
throw new InvalidArgumentException(
\sprintf("Invalid email: %s", $value)
);
}
$this->value = \strtolower($value);
}
}
Combined with constructor property promotion, readonly removes much of the boilerplate:
final class Percentage
{
public function __construct(
public readonly float $value
) {
if ($value < 0 || $value > 100) {
throw new InvalidArgumentException(
'Percentage must be between 0 and 100'
);
}
}
}The object becomes self-protecting: once a valid Percentage exists, its value cannot silently change.
In PHP 8.2+, readonly class can take this even further by making every property readonly automatically.
▶︎ Enums
Not every domain concept needs a full Value Object. Sometimes the concept is simply a fixed set of possible values.
For these cases, PHP enums are often a better choice because the language itself enforces the allowed values.
